Here is a JavaScript function that uses regular expressions to extract a three-character code from a filename:

```javascript
function extractCode(filename) {
    // Regular expression pattern to match the filename format "xx-1Jn.usfm"
    const pattern = /^(\d|[\w]{3})\.usfm$/i;

    // Use the RegExp.exec() method to search for the first occurrence of the pattern in the filename
    const match = pattern.exec(filename);

    if (match) {
        return match[1]; // Return the matched code
    } else {
        return null; // Return null if no match found
    }
}

// Example usage:
const filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
console.log(extractCode(filename)); // Output: "1Jn"
```

Here's a breakdown of how the regular expression pattern works:

* `^` matches the start of the string
* `(\d|[\w]{3})` captures one or three alphanumeric characters (digits, letters) in group 1
* `\.` matches the dot (`.`) character literally
* `usfm` matches the literal string "usfm"
* `$` matches the end of the string

The `i` flag at the end of the pattern makes it case-insensitive.
